         <abstract>
            <p>We present an empirical analysis of the subsequent disposition and share price performance of 142 firms involved in proxy contests for board seats in the period 1962-1986. We find evidence that proxy contests increase corporate efficiency through improved monitoring of firms, even in the absence of takeover-related control activity. Our results support the view that proxy contests are an effective managerial disciplinary mechanism in the absence of a takeover.</p>
         </abstract>
